When you run the openssl req command to create a self-signed certificate, it will prompt you to provide several details. Below is an example of how to fill in these details with realistic, industry-standard values for a company:


---

Details Prompted During the Command

You are about to be asked to enter information that will be incorporated
into your certificate request.
What you are about to enter is what is called a Distinguished Name or a DN.
There are quite a few fields but you can leave some blank.
For some fields, there will be a default value.

Country Name (2 letter code) [AU]:
State or Province Name (full name) [Some-State]:
Locality Name (eg, city) []:
Organization Name (eg, company) [Internet Widgits Pty Ltd]:
Organizational Unit Name (eg, section) []:
Common Name (e.g. server FQDN or YOUR name) []:
Email Address []:


---

Example Input for an IT Organization

Country Name (2 letter code) [AU]: US
State or Province Name (full name) [Some-State]: New York
Locality Name (eg, city) []: New York City
Organization Name (eg, company) [Internet Widgits Pty Ltd]: Tech Solutions Inc.
Organizational Unit Name (eg, section) []: IT Operations
Common Name (e.g. server FQDN or YOUR name) []: www.techsolutions.com
Email Address []: admin@techsolutions.com


---

Field Explanation

1. Country Name (2-letter code):

Enter the 2-letter ISO code of your country.

Example: US for United States, IN for India, UK for United Kingdom.



2. State or Province Name:

Full name of the state or province where the organization is located.

Example: New York, California, Delhi.



3. Locality Name (City):

Name of the city where your organization is based.

Example: New York City, San Francisco, Bangalore.



4. Organization Name:

The official name of your organization.

Example: Tech Solutions Inc., Acme Corp, XYZ Pvt Ltd.



5. Organizational Unit Name:

Department or division within the organization.

Example: IT Operations, Web Services, DevOps Team.



6. Common Name (CN):

The Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN) or public IP address of your server.

Example: www.techsolutions.com, app.techsolutions.com, 192.168.1.1.



7. Email Address:

Administrative email address to contact in case of certificate issues.

Example: admin@techsolutions.com, support@techsolutions.com.





---

Resulting Certificate

After filling in these details, the command will generate:

selfsigned.key: The private key.

selfsigned.crt: The self-signed certificate containing the provided information.


These files can now be used to configure SSL in Nginx or other web servers.
